column1: <td id="LC145" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Irish Water working in partnership with Galway County Council is restricting water supply to the Carna/Kilkieran
column3: and Rós Muc water supplies tonight from 10pm until 9am tomorrow morning as well as the Laurencetown and Eyrecourt zones of the Ballinasloe Regional Water Supply. Unprecedented demand due to taps being left running is causing reservoir levels to drop. We are appealing to customers to turn off taps and check for leaks on their own properties and in holiday homes and unoccupied premises and to report them to Irish Water’s customer care helpline on 1850 278 278.

column1: <td id="LC147" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">The Carraroe water supply was restored to customers today following water restrictions on the scheme yesterday and overnight. The reservoirs have filled sufficiently to allow supply to return however
column2: due to increased demand restrictions will be in place again tonight and for the next few nights until demand regularises and the water treatment plant can meet the demand needs. It may take several hours for all sections of the network to get water supply once it is restored again in the morning. Water supply to the village and the nursing home is being maintained at all times.

column1: <td id="LC149" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Irish Water is grateful to Galway Fire Service who delivered bottled water out to Carraroe yesterday evening on behalf of the utility and the local fire service distributed it to vulnerable customers.
<td id="LC151" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Across Co Galway customers are being advised that due to the extremely cold weather conditions and exceptionally high water demand
column2: water treatment plants are struggling to keep up with supply demands.

column1: <td id="LC153" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Customers are being asked to conserve water to avoid reservoirs emptying and water pressure to homes and businesses being affected.

<td id="LC155" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Night time restrictions on the Tully and Letterfrack supplies has enabled the reservoirs to refill to some degree and full supply has been restored this morning. Irish Water would like to thank customers supplied by these schemes for adhering to our water conservation notice yesterday. There will be further restrictions on this scheme tonight.

<td id="LC157" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">A repair crew travelled to Inishbofin this morning (Saturday) to carry out repairs to a mechanical fault at the plant. The plant is back in production with limited capacity. There will be water restrictions in place tonight. Customers on the island are urged to conserve water. Bottled water was delivered to the island today.

<td id="LC159" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Williamstown is suffering a major water supply issue due to a leak in the town. Leak repair crews were unable to find the leak today. Supply will be rotated to customers in the area over the coming days and customers will experience intermittent disruptions and/or loss of supply.
<td id="LC161" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">In East Galway customers are again urged to conserve water by turning off taps in properties and farm buildings
column2: not running dishwashers or washing machines where possible and taking showers instead of baths.

column1: <td id="LC163" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Irish Water is appealing to any customers with external taps to ensure that these are securely turned off as we try to protect the levels of our reservoirs and secure drinking water for local communities. A continuous flow from an external tap over a 24 hour period could use the equivalent of the daily water usage of 40 households.

<td id="LC165" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">The following areas are experiencing low pressure and/or loss of supply due to an increase in demand and some issues at treatment plants: Kilkerrin/Moylough

<td id="LC167" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Irish Water working in partnership with Galway County Council would like to apologise to customers for the inconvenience this is causing and assures customers that repairs will be completed as soon as possible. Irish Water would also like to thank the local authority staff for their efforts in keeping water supplies running in very difficult conditions.

<td id="LC169" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Once further information is available we will issue another update. Updates will also be posted to the supply and service section of Irish Water’s website at www.water.ie/water-supply/supply-and-service-update/"

the blizzard conditions have passed and the public safety advice to shelter indoors is withdrawn.

column4: "The front page of this Friday’s Galway City Tribune. It’ll be in shops as soon as it’s safe for our delivery team. It will also be available to buy online from early morning at:

column1: <td id="LC268" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Priority is to deploy available resources to keep roads clear and ensure essential services. Salting recommenced in last hour. We're working closely with Cope in relation to getting rough sleepers into our Cold Weather service in the Westside.  Staff continuously monitoring situation. Stay safe and stay indoors. Emergency calls to 091 536400.

<td id="LC270" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Galway City Council's Weather Assessment and Response Team has met each day this week to assess the current and forecasted situation regarding the current snow and ice warnings and other weather related issues. The Team met again at lunchtime today.
<td id="LC274" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">There is a status Red warning Snow/Ice that applies to Galway City currently in place and up to 6.00am on Friday
<td id="LC278" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">5 -day rainfall and temperature forecasts were assessed (www.met.ie).

<td id="LC279" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Temperatures are expected to fall below 0 (freezing) in coming days with temperatures falling as low as -4 degrees on the morning of Thurs. 1st Mar.

<td id="LC280" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Light precipitation was forecast from evening of Wed. 28th Feb. increasing to medium heavy by morning of Fri. 2nd Mar. Coupled with low temperatures this precipitation will most likely be snow.
<td id="LC284" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">The OPW issued a high tide advisory notice for the period of Thurs. 1st Mar. to Mon. 5th Mar.
<td id="LC286" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Galway City Council are aware of the current period of very high astronomical spring tides.

<td id="LC287" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">The highest astronomical tide in this period will occur on Sat. 3 rd Mar. '18 - accurate predicted water levels are not yet available for this date.
<td id="LC289" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Actions/Measures in place:
<td id="LC291" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">If anyone is in need of a bed overnight
column2: our #ColdWeatherResponse is in place for rough sleepers with @COPEGalway Contact 1800 788887 (7pm to 11pm) & 085 8009641 (9pm+)

column1: <td id="LC293" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">The Winter Maintenance Programme for roads across the city is on-going. It is intended that salting operations will continue. Currently being salted on National and principle regional routes in and across the city .The situation will be monitored for following days. Galway City Council has an ample supply (and reserve stock) of salt.
<td id="LC295" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">The main pedestrianised streets in the city centre have been salted and the status of the streets will be monitored thereafter.

<td id="LC297" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">The Infrastructure section will monitor tide levels and keep in contact with the Harbour Master during this period of high astronomical spring tides

<td id="LC298" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">The Aquadam bund at Fishmarket will be partially inflated and roads crews will be on standby (for road closures etc.) in the event of overtopping/flooding due to tides particularly early on Saturday morning 3rd March.
<td id="LC299" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">A Follow Up Meeting of the Weather assessment Team is scheduled for early on Friday morning with staff and crews on standby."
<td id="LC302" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">I want to pay tribute today to our outstanding health service staff all over the country for their incredible dedication and commitment.

<td id="LC304" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">They are going to huge efforts to keep vital services open and ensure patients are looked after in very difficult conditions. From across Ireland I have heard stories today of health care workers walking to work
column4: and going above and beyond the call of duty to ensure their patients get the care they need.

column1: <td id="LC306" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">I would also like to thank our paramedics for transporting patients in very difficult conditions
column2: Civil Defence staff for helping deliver crucial medication and the Defence Forces for transferring dialysis patients and medicines
column3: as well as helping our dedicated health staff to get to work safely.

column1: <td id="LC308" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Let us all support our committed health care staff by ensuring we keep emergencies for emergencies.
<td id="LC310" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">I would also like to take this opportunity to appeal to people to check in on your vulnerable friends
column3: when it’s safe to do so
column4: to make sure they are well and warm."""

<td id="LC336" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Following the upgrade of the weather warning last night by Met Eireann to Status Red for the entire country today (Thursday March 1st)
column2: Galway University Hospitals (University Hospital Galway and Merlin Park University Hospital) and Portiuncula University Hospital have cancelled routine electives and outpatient appointments today and tomorrow (Friday 2nd).

column1: <td id="LC338" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">The hospitals are putting arrangements in place to ensure the continuation of essential services for chemotherapy and dialysis patients as well as those coming in for urgent surgery. These patients are being prioritised at this time and are being contacted by the clinical teams in relation to appointments/procedures planned for today and tomorrow. In circumstances where patients are unable to travel
column2: alternative dates will be provided as soon as possible.

column1: <td id="LC340" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">In relation to the renal service in Merlin Park
column2: we are in contact with transport providers for dialysis patients with regard to the weather conditions. Patients will be contacted individually and decisions will be based on clinical need and the travel advice from the National Emergency Co-ordination Group.

column1: <td id="LC342" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">We will continue to do everything possible to maintain all essential services to patients receiving planned cancer and renal services. All appointments cancelled during this period will be rescheduled and we will be in contact directly with patients to reschedule their appointments.
<td id="LC344" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Patients should be advised that if they do attend the hospital today for a clinic appointment they will be seen.

column2: radiotherapy patients should attend for their scheduled treatment in UHG.

column1: <td id="LC348" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">The hospitals’ Emergency Departments continues to be busy and we expect difficulties around discharge planning as a consequence of the adverse conditions.

<td id="LC349" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">We would ask that patients who are being discharged today are collected from the hospital as early as possible to avoid travelling during the worsening conditions forecast for this afternoon

<td id="LC351" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">We would encourage people to consider all options available to them for their healthcare needs and to protect the ED for those most seriously ill as delays can be expected.
<td id="LC353" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">GUH and PUH are working closely with colleagues in the Community Health Organisations and with the National Ambulance Service."

"Update 11pm: STATUS RED WARNING NOW IN PLACE NATIONWIDE

column1: <td id="LC399" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">CITY COUNCIL WEATHER UPDATE:

<td id="LC401" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Galway City Council’s Weather Assessment and Response Team has met each day this week to assess the current and forecasted situation regarding the current snow and ice warnings and other weather related issues. The Team met again on Wednesday afternoon with members of the Senior Management Team of GCC in attendance. An assessment of the current situation follows along with the actions being undertaken by City Council staff.
<td id="LC404" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">There are 2 weather warnings (www.met.ie)  in place that apply to Galway City:
<td id="LC405" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">·          A Status Orange warning for snow ice for Galway valid from 5pm Wed. 28th Feb. to 12noon on Thurs 1st Mar.

<td id="LC406" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">·         A Status Orange warning for snow ice for Connacht valid 8pm on Thurs. 1st Mar. to 12noon on Fri. 2nd Mar. This warns of persistent snow showers in this period which together with strong easterly winds may lead to snow drifts.
<td id="LC408" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">The 2 Status Red warnings in place do not apply to Galway.
<td id="LC413" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">·         5 -day rainfall and temperature forecasts were assessed (www.met.ie).

<td id="LC414" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">·         Temperatures are expected to fall below 0 (freezing) in coming days with temperatures expected to fall as low as -4 degrees on the morning of Thurs. 1st Mar.

<td id="LC415" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">·         Light precipitation is forecast from evening of Wed. 28th Feb.  increasing to light-medium by morning of Fri. 2nd Mar. Coupled with low temperatures this precipitation will most likely be snow.
<td id="LC418" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">·         The OPW issued a high tide advisory notice for the period of Thurs. 1st Mar. to Mon. 5th Mar.
<td id="LC419" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">·         Galway City Council are aware of the period of the current period of very high astronomical spring tides.

<td id="LC420" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">·         The highest astronomical tide in this period will occur on Sat. 3rd Mar. ’18 – accurate predicted water levels are not yet available for this date.
<td id="LC423" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Actions/Measures in place:

<td id="LC425" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">·         The Winter Maintenance Programme for roads across the city is on-going. It is intended that salting operations will take place 7-9pm tonight and again at 5am tomorrow morning (Thurs. 1st Mar. ’18). The situation will be monitored for following days. Galway City council has an ample supply (and reserve stock) of salt.

<td id="LC426" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">·         Requests have come in for salting on roads in estates and carparks in churches (in advance of religious events at the weekend).  The Roads section will facilitate such requests as best as possible.

<td id="LC427" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">·         The main pedestrianised streets in the city centre will be salted on Thursday morning and the status of the streets will be monitored thereafter.

<td id="LC428" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">·         The roads section will monitor water levels and keep in contact with the Harbour Master during this period of high astronomical spring tides

<td id="LC429" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">·         The Aquadam bund at Fishmarket  will be partially inflated and roads crews will be on standby (for road closures etc.) in the event of overtopping/flooding due to tides particularly early on Saturday morning 3rd March.
<td id="LC430" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">·           A Follow Up Meeting of the Weather assessment Team is scheduled for 2.30pm on Thurs. 1st Mar. ‘18"

column1: <td id="LC1077" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Mouth cancer is an important global healthcare problem. There are more than 300 cases of cancer of the mouth (oral cavity and pharynx) reported in Ireland every year. These cancers are more common in men than in women. However this is changing.

<td id="LC1079" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">The incidence rate of cancer of the mouth in women has increased significantly at a rate of 3% per year since 1994. It mainly affects older people although younger people are being diagnosed now. In Britain
column2: the incidence of mouth cancer has increased faster than any other cancer in the past 25 years.

column1: <td id="LC1081" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">According to the National Cancer Registry in Ireland
column2: roughly half of all mouth cancers and even less of cancers of the pharynx are diagnosed at an early stage.

column1: <td id="LC1083" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">This can result in more complex treatment with greater impact on quality of life and overall survival. Whilst it depends on the cancer site we know that more than half of those treated will have good survival outcomes and this continues to improve each year.
<td id="LC1085" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Early detection of mouth cancer greatly improves the chances of survival.

<td id="LC1087" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Dentists have a key role to play in the early detection of mouth cancer and in the prevention of the disease by identifying those patients who are exposed to risk factors.
<td id="LC1089" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Mouth Cancer Awareness Day is Wednesday

<td id="LC1091" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Please consult your dentist during your routine dental visit about a mouth cancer examination - taking 10 minutes that could save your life."

column4: "FT: Galway 0-13 0-13 Dublin. A dramatic Johnny Heaney point eight minutes into injury time secured Galway a draw against 14 man Dublin in Salthill. Galway were up by two going into added time before Dublin reeled off three points to take a one point advantage. Eoghan O'Gara was red carded for Dublin after an off the ball incident with Sean Andy. The Tribesmen are still unbeaten in this year's league campaign. C'MON GALWAY! #GALvDUB"

"55 mins: Galway 0-10 0-8 Dublin. It is tight and tough in Salthill. Dublin have narrowed the gap to two points but Galway are frustrating the Dubs. Worryingly though Galway have not troubled the score keepers this half. Dean Rock was given a black card for a deliberate pull down. C'MON GALWAY! #GALvDUB"

"HT: Galway 0-10 0-5 Dublin. The Tribesmen are up by five against the All-Ireland champions. Dublin have tried to bore everyone into submission by holding onto the ball and refusing to attack. column4: "Galway United return to action at Eamonn Deacy Park tonight (Friday) when the Tribesmen face Cabinteely. Kick-off is at 7.45pm at the Corribside venue.

column1: <td id="LC1447" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Friday's league encounter will be the first competitive meeting of the two sides.
<td id="LC1449" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Cabinteely have lost both of their opening league games by a single goal against Wexford and Cobh Ramblers.
<td id="LC1451" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">United meanwhile were held by UCD last week
column3: after recording a convincing 4-1 win against Athlone Town on the first night of the season and Shane Keegan is targeting another league win at Eamonn Deacy Park against Pat Devlin's side.

column1: <td id="LC1453" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Keegan warns about complacency —
<td id="LC1455" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">""The thing that I was hammering home to the players is
column2: Cabinteely are a team that have lacked the rub of the green over their two opening games
column3: rather than playing poorly in them.

column1: <td id="LC1457" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">""It makes them dangerous opposition for us
column2: they're desperate to get points on the board. That bit of luck that might've alluded them is possibly due to swing around soon
column3: so it really is important that our player don't think that we're facing a team who are struggling. We've got to be at our best
column4: or it will be a serious banana skin for us.

column1: <td id="LC1459" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">""When you have aspirations of trying to win this division or attain promotion
column2: realistically you're looking to try and win every home game. You're going into your home games with a level of expectation of delivering a performance and the three points.

column1: <td id="LC1461" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">""Hopefully the Cabinteely game will be no different. If we can get a regular big crowd behind us at home
column2: it's definitely a big help to us.

column4: "University Hospital Galway is again reminding the public about visitor restrictions currently in place in a number of wards in the hospital due to suspected cases of the vomiting bug (Norovirus). In order to assist staff in curtailing the spread of this virus
column5: it is imperative that only essential visiting takes place in St Mary’s ward
column6: St Anthony’s ward and St Enda’s ward during this period.

column1: <td id="LC1645" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Children should not visit the hospital as they may be particularly susceptible to the illness.

<td id="LC1647" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">We are asking that visitors are requested to cooperate with hospital staff who are ensuring the restrictions are adhered to and visitors are also advised that they must use the alcohol hand gels supplied as they enter and leave the hospital. Infection control procedures are in place on the affected wards and will remain so until further notice.

<td id="LC1649" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">There continues to be an increase in the number of cases of Norovirus in the community and anyone with recent symptoms of diarrhoea and/or vomiting or who has had contact with others who have these symptoms should not visit patients in the hospital to avoid spreading the virus to sick vulnerable patients.

<td id="LC1651" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">The Emergency Department at University Hospital Galway continues to be extremely busy and we apologise that patients are experiencing delays. We would encourage people to consider all options available to them for their healthcare needs and to protect the ED for those most seriously ill."

"Irish Water working in partnership with Galway County Council would like to advise customers on the following public water supplies that restrictions will be in place again tonight to allow reservoirs replenish and to ensure water supply tomorrow: Tully
column7: Carraroe (supply being maintained in the village and to the nursing home)

column1: <td id="LC1687" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Restrictions to water supplies are necessary where demand is outstripping supply so reservoirs have the opportunity to replenish over night and therefore ensuring customers receive a water supply during the day.
<td id="LC1689" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Customers are being asked to conserve water by turning off taps
column3: limiting usage of washing machines and dishwashers where possible and taking showers instead of baths
column4: to avoid reservoirs emptying and water pressure to homes and businesses being affected.

Kiltormer and Clonfert areas will be without a water supply today and tomorrow (Wednesday). Consumption has increased by 50 per cent in this area and customers are urged to conserve water in every way possible. Water supply will be maintained to Ballinasloe town and Portiuncula Hospital.

column1: <td id="LC1693" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Alternative water supplies will be available in Eyrecourt
column3: Clonfert and Kiltormer and bottled water will be distributed to vulnerable customers who have self-registered with Irish Water.

column1: <td id="LC1695" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">There will be two tankers in the Square
<td id="LC1696" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">There will be one tanker each at the Community Hall Laurencetown
column2: Clonfert Church and Kiltormer Church from 6pm.

column1: <td id="LC1697" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Kiltormer Nursing Home will also be attended to.
<td id="LC1698" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Bottled water was delivered to Eyrecourt
<td id="LC1700" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Irish Water makes every effort to ensure that the alternative drinking water supply provided
column5: as it is not practical to provide sterilised containers for the public to transport drinking water from the tanker to their homes and we cannot guarantee that any containers used by the public do not negatively impact or contaminate the drinking water. Therefore people are advised to boil this water before use.

column1: <td id="LC1701" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">In Carraroe night time restrictions will continue over the coming days. This will be managed locally to ensure water supply is rotated around the scheme.
<td id="LC1703" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Restrictions will continue over the coming days in Tully and Letterfrack
column2: but supply will be on for the full daytime period and the situation is improving.

column1: <td id="LC1705" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Some customers are receiving intermittent supply in Tír an Fhia due to excessive demand. Restrictions will continue over the coming days. Bottled water will be delivered to customers who are without any supply in high lying areas tomorrow (Wednesday) and to vulnerable customers who have self-registered with Irish Water.
<td id="LC1707" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Restrictions will be in place in Rós Muc and Moylough again tonight due to excessive demand on the scheme.

<td id="LC1709" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Leak repairs are still being undertaken in Williamstown. High leakage on customers’ properties is also being addressed. Supply will continue to be rotated to customers in the area over the coming days and customers will experience intermittent disruptions and/or loss of supply.

<td id="LC1711" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Across Galway there are issues with high demand. Irish Water is appealing to customers to turn off taps and check for leaks on their own properties and in holiday homes and unoccupied premises and to report them to Irish Water’s customer care helpline on 1850 278 278. Irish Water is appealing to any customers with external taps to ensure that these are securely turned off as we try to protect the levels of our reservoirs and secure drinking water for local communities. A continuous flow from an external tap over a 24 hour period could use the equivalent of the daily water usage of 40 households.

"Statement from Galway University Hospitals and Portiuncula University Hospital relating to the status red weather warning

column1: <td id="LC2042" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Following the upgrade of the weather warning last night by Met Eireann to Status Red for the entire country today (Thursday March 1st)
column2: Galway University Hospitals (University Hospital Galway and Merlin Park University Hospital) and Portiuncula University Hospital have cancelled routine electives and outpatient appointments today and tomorrow (Friday 2nd).

column1: <td id="LC2044" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">The hospitals are putting arrangements in place to ensure the continuation of essential services for chemotherapy and dialysis patients as well as those coming in for urgent surgery. These patients are being prioritised at this time and are being contacted by the clinical teams in relation to appointments/procedures planned for today and tomorrow. In circumstances where patients are unable to travel
column2: alternative dates will be provided as soon as possible.

column1: <td id="LC2046" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">In relation to the renal service in Merlin Park
column2: we are in contact with transport providers for dialysis patients with regard to the weather conditions. Patients will be contacted individually and decisions will be based on clinical need and the travel advice from the National Emergency Co-ordination Group.

column1: <td id="LC2048" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">We will continue to do everything possible to maintain all essential services to patients receiving planned cancer and renal services. All appointments cancelled during this period will be rescheduled and we will be in contact directly with patients to reschedule their appointments.
<td id="LC2050" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Patients should be advised that if they do attend the hospital today for a clinic appointment they will be seen.

<td id="LC2052" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">The hospitals’ Emergency Departments continues to be busy and we expect difficulties around discharge planning as a consequence of the adverse conditions.

<td id="LC2053" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">We would ask that patients who are being discharged today are collected from the hospital as early as possible to avoid travelling during the worsening conditions forecast for this afternoon

<td id="LC2055" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">We would encourage people to consider all options available to them for their healthcare needs and to protect the ED for those most seriously ill as delays can be expected.
<td id="LC2057" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">GUH and PUH are working closely with colleagues in the Community Health Organisations and with the National Ambulance Service.

<td id="LC2060" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Keep up to date with @HSELive and @saoltagroup on Twitter and visit www.hse.ie/weatherwarning or www.saolta.ie for all the latest information regarding health services"
<td id="LC2062" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">The O'Donnellan & Joyce auction due to take place today at The Harbour Hotel has been postponed until FRIDAY 9TH MARCH."

"Galway City Council’s Weather Assessment and Response Team has met each day this week to assess the current and forecasted situation regarding the current snow and ice warnings and other weather related issues. The Team met again on Wednesday afternoon with members of the Senior Management Team of GCC in attendance. An assessment of the current situation follows along with the actions being undertaken by City Council staff.

column1: <td id="LC2108" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">There are 2 weather warnings (www.met.ie)  in place that apply to Galway City:
<td id="LC2109" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">·          A Status Yellow warning for snow ice for Connacht valid 8am Wed. 28th Feb. to 12noon on Thurs 1st Mar.

<td id="LC2110" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">·         A Status Orange warning for snow ice for Connacht valid 8pm on Thurs. 1st Mar. to 12noon on 12 noon on Fri. 2nd Mar. This warns of persistent snow showers in this period which together with strong easterly winds may lead to snow drifts.
<td id="LC2112" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">The 2 Status Red warnings in place do not apply to Galway.
<td id="LC2117" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">·         5 -day rainfall and temperature forecasts were assessed (www.met.ie).

<td id="LC2118" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">·         Temperatures are expected to fall below 0 (freezing) in coming days with temperatures expected to fall as low as -4 degrees on the morning of Thurs. 1st Mar.

<td id="LC2119" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">·         Light precipitation is forecast from evening of Wed. 28th Feb.  increasing to light-medium by morning of Fri. 2nd Mar. Coupled with low temperatures this precipitation will most likely be snow.
<td id="LC2122" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">·         The OPW issued a high tide advisory notice for the period of Thurs. 1st Mar. to Mon. 5th Mar.
<td id="LC2123" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">·         Galway City Council are aware of the period of the current period of very high astronomical spring tides.

<td id="LC2124" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">·         The highest astronomical tide in this period will occur on Sat. 3rd Mar. ’18 – accurate predicted water levels are not yet available for this date.
<td id="LC2127" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Actions/Measures in place:

<td id="LC2129" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">·         The Winter Maintenance Programme for roads across the city is on-going. It is intended that salting operations will take place 7-9pm tonight and again at 5am tomorrow morning (Thurs. 1st Mar. ’18). The situation will be monitored for following days. Galway City council has an ample supply (and reserve stock) of salt.

<td id="LC2130" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">·         Requests have come in for salting on roads in estates and carparks in churches (in advance of religious events at the weekend).  The Roads section will facilitate such requests as best as possible.

<td id="LC2131" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">·         The main pedestrianised streets in the city centre will be salted on Thursday morning and the status of the streets will be monitored thereafter.

<td id="LC2132" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">·         The roads section will monitor water levels and keep in contact with the Harbour Master during this period of high astronomical spring tides

<td id="LC2133" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">·         The Aquadam bund at Fishmarket  will be partially inflated and roads crews will be on standby (for road closures etc.) in the event of overtopping/flooding due to tides particularly early on Saturday morning 3rd March.
<td id="LC2134" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">·           A Follow Up Meeting of the Weather assessment Team is scheduled for 2.30pm on Thurs. 1st Mar. ‘18

column2: here is a description of each of the status warnings used by Met Éireann

column1: <td id="LC2139" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">STATUS YELLOW - Weather Alert - Be Aware
<td id="LC2141" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">The concept behind YELLOW level weather alerts is to notify those who are at risk because of their location and/or activity
column2: and to allow them to take preventative action. It is implicit that YELLOW level weather alerts are for weather conditions that do not pose an immediate threat to the general population
column3: but only to those exposed to risk by nature of their location and/or activity.

column1: <td id="LC2143" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">STATUS ORANGE - Weather Warning - Be Prepared

<td id="LC2145" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">This category of ORANGE level weather warnings is for weather conditions which have the capacity to impact significantly on people in the affected areas. The issue of an Orange level weather warning implies that all recipients in the affected areas should prepare themselves in an appropriate way for the anticipated conditions.
<td id="LC2147" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">STATUS RED - Severe Weather Warning - Take Action

<td id="LC2149" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">The issue of RED level severe weather warnings should be a comparatively rare event and implies that recipients take action to protect themselves and/or their properties; this could be by moving their families out of the danger zone temporarily; by staying indoors; or by other specific actions aimed at mitigating the effects of the weather conditions."

column1: <td id="LC2350" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Solo Atlantic Rower Damian Browne is now only hours away from the Finish Line of the Talisker Whisky Atlantic Challenge.  His current ETA is 6.30pm Irish Time.  The former Leinster and Connacht Rugby star set off on his 4
column3: 14th December from the Canary Islands and will finish in Antigua.  The Solo Atlantic Rower has now been at sea with his boat Gulliver’s Travels for nine weeks.

column1: <td id="LC2351" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Damian has taken on the challenge as an extreme trial of his mental and physical strength.  As a solo rower there has been no support boat and no company for Damian
column2: just himself and a boatload of food to sustain him on his journey.  He is also rowing in an effort to raise funds for his chosen charities MADRA Dog Rescue & Adoption
column3: Médecins Sans Frontieres and the Strong Roots Foundation School Rwanda.

column1: <td id="LC2352" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">Two days ago
column2: the 37-year-old - who has regularly been posting videos and updates along the way - admitted he was feeling the effects of life on the ocean as he entered the final 100 nautical miles.  ""Last three mornings have been the hardest of the journey
column3: "" he said ""imagine it: alarm summons you from the only semi dry place on the boat
column4: your bed.  You pull on soaking wet shorts
column5: base layer and wet suit top and climb out into the craziness.  The ever present howling wind and raging seas (are) now joined by frequent squalls and arse sores back with vengeance. It won’t be sunrise for four hours .... ignore the pain
